{{refimprove|date=January 2017}} {{Infobox company | name = Ceriani or Arces | logo = | type = | genre = | fate = Dissolved, brand sold to [[Paioli]] | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = [[Italy]] ({{Start date|1951}}) | founder = Arturo Ceriani | defunct = {{End date|1980}} | location_city = [[Samarate]] | location_country = Italy | location = | locations = | area_served = | key_people = | industry = [[Manufacturing]] | products = Motorcycle frames, suspensions | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = | subsid = | homepage = | footnotes = | intl = }} [[File:LaverdaCerianiBrembo1974.jpg|thumb|upright|Telescoping hydraulic frame fork by Ceriani mounted on a 1974 [[Laverda|Laverda 1000]], with [[Brembo]] twin disc brakes]] '''Ceriani''', formerly '''Arces''', was an Italian company that designed and fabricated [[motorcycle]] frames and [[Suspension (motorcycle)|suspensions]]. The company was founded by Arturo Ceriani in 1951.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Arces is an acronym derived from '''A'''rturo '''Ce'''riani [[Società a Responsabilità Limitata|'''S'''.r.l.]]<ref>{{Citation |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=U_taRN9B4HIC&pg=PA70 |page=70 |title= Motorbike Suspensions: Modern design and optimisation |first1= Dario |last1= Croccolo|first2= Massimiliano |last2= Agostinis |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |year= 2013 |ISBN=9781447151494 }}</ref>
In the European motorcycle industry, it was common for many smaller parts companies to exist, each responsible for creating individual parts to later be assembled into a complete motorcycle. Within a few years of its creation, Ceriani's company was able to successfully make a name for itself by manufacturing components noted for their quality and vision.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}
In 1964, under the leadership of Arturo's son Enrico Ceriani, the companies operations were expanded.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Enrico accelerated the expansion by moving the company to a new and more modern plant in [[Samarate]].{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} From 1964 the company was known within the industry as ARCES (an acronym of ARturo CEriani Samarate) but the [[brand identity]] was maintained and the company continued to be known as Ceriani by [[consumer]]s.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}
A central development in the new plant was the creation of a team that was dedicated to studying and designing new solutions for the suspension systems and frames of [[Motorcycle racing|competition motorcycles]].{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}
In the late 1960s, Ceriani began to produce an innovative new type of fork slider made of a light [[alloy]] for use in competition and a revolutionary type of telescopic hydraulic suspension that was originally used on [[motocross]] bikes but was later applied to [[types of motorcycle#Street|street motorcycles]].{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}
The demand for the new suspension was so high that ARCES output had doubled compared to the year before.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} The new technology exploded onto the market and by 1972 Ceriani had sold 100,000 suspension units, 30,000 to competition motorcycles and 70,000 to consumer street bikes. {{citation needed|date=February 2016}}
In the late 1970s, Ceriani experienced a rapid and unexpected decline during the overall crisis in the European manufacturing sector due to increased demand that stressed the capabilities of smaller companies.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Other companies were able to successfully adapt and fill the [[niche market|niche]] of competition motorcycle parts manufacturing that was left vacant by Ceriani's inability to effectively meet rising [[demand]].{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}
Ceriani was not able to recover to the changing market and their plant closed down in 1980.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} The prestigious Ceriani [[brand name]] was bought in 1997 by Italian motorcycle parts maker [[Paioli]].{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}
